National and Seasonal Effects on COVID Deaths

Oscar Rivera

3/1/2022

Introduction

When the COVID-19 virus made its presence in North America, it was very quick to make a negative impact on the nations in this continent, with those nations being the United States, Canada, and Mexico. Having settled in these nations, the virus brought a significant number of infections and deaths to those living in these nations within first two years of its presence. Throughout these two years, there were certain time periods in which the number of deaths due to COVID rose up drastically. Furthermore, these number of deaths turned out to be much higher for some nations. Since the virus became a threat to the world, The World Health Organization (WHO) has been monitoring the number of deaths and cases per for various countries around the globe. The data set which WHO uses to keep track of these number can observed through the weekly WHO COVID-19 update. For this project, we will focus on determining whether the nations in North America and the seasons of the year have major effects on the number of deaths caused by COVID-19 during the pandemic.

Background

The data set that we will be working with to answer the following question is WHO COVID-19 data set that was mentioned in the introduction. Through this data set, WHO has managed to keep track of the daily and cumulative number of COVID cases and deaths between January 20202 to present day as well as for all nations across the globe.

Since our question of interest is focused on countries in North America, we minimized the observations to those involving the United States, Canada, and Mexico. Around March 2020, the number of COVID cases and deaths became more recognized in North America in the sense that the nations in this continent began taking serious measures to control for these number. With this being said, I have restricted this data set to dates between March 1, 2020 to February 28, 2022. In addition, applying this restriction on the data set give more flexibility to use appropriate methods in my analysis, which will be discussed later.

To create a variable for season, we used the month number of the dates listed in the data. All observations with month numbers 1, 2, or 12 are assigned. Winter for season, all dates with month numbers 3, 4, or 5 are assigned Spring for season, all dates with month numbers 6, 7, or 8 are assigned Summer for season, and all dates with month numbers 9, 10, and 11 are assigned Fall for season. Using the number of deaths and the number of cases per day, we constructed a variable for case-fatality rate (CFR) per day, which is defined as \[ CFR = \dfrac{\text{Number of COVID deaths per day}}{\text{Number of COVID deaths per day}} \] Viewing the WHO data set, one will notice that the for some dates, the number of cases are zero. For those dates, we set the CFR equal to zero.

Exploratory Data Analysis

Restricting the WHO data to the United States, Canada, and Mexico and to the dates March 1 2020 - February 28 2022, the modified data set contains 2190 total observations.

Time Series Plots

To study the daily number of deaths, cases, and case-fatality rates due to COVID within a span of two years, I created a times series plot of these numbers for all three nations.

Looking at the time series plot of the COVID deaths for the three nations (topleft), all three countries appear to show similar trends. In all time periods, Canada tends to have the lowest number of deaths despite being the largest country from the three. Although it seems that COVID deaths are higher for the US, one can see that these numbers for all three nations tend to fluctuate roughly around the same time of the year. This may be an indication that the seasons of each year may play a role on the number of deaths rising up so rapidly. In the time series plot of the COVID cases for the three countries (topright), the US tends to have the highest number of cases. Further, it shows that the US had quite some time periods where the cases got significantly high. Near the ending of this plot, one can observe that the cases for all three nation increased around the same time period. In the time series plot of the CFR for the three countries (bottomleft), Mexico appears to have the highest CFR. Note that Canada has a very high CFR value for one of the dates. The reason for the CFR being that high is because on that day, there two COVID cases and one COVID, leading to \(CFR=1/2\). The date corresponding to this is March 11, 2020, which is the day Canada reported its first COVID death.

Interaction Plot of Average COVID Deaths by Country and Season

To examine the effects these seasons and nations have on the death number created an interaction plot of the average COVID deaths numbers by season and nationality.

The differences in the heights of the four curves reflects the seasonal effects on deaths, and the deviation from horizontal reflects the effects of nationality on deaths. The plot indicates that there may be effects from nationality and season present in the number deaths caused by COVID. The curves for Winter, Fall, and Spring appear to have similar behaviors look to be nearly parallel. However, one may notice that the curves for for Fall, Spring, and Summer appear to intersect on the left portion of the plot. Also, the curve for Summer intersects with both the curves of Fall and Spring in between Mexico and US. This observation points out that there may be an Nationality-Seasonal interaction effect on the number of deaths.

Model Proposal

To determine whether the nations in North America and the seasons in a calendar year have major effects on the number of deaths caused by COVID-19, we will be using a balanced Two-Way ANOVA model. A balanced Two-Way ANOVA model in factor-effect is written in the following form: \[ Y_{ijk} = \mu + \alpha_i + \beta_j + (\alpha \beta)_{ij} + \epsilon_{ijk}, \ i = 1, \dots, a; \ \ j = 1, \ldots, b; \ \ k = 1, \ldots, n_{ij}. \] where, \(\alpha_i\) is the fixed main effect of factor A at the \(i\)th level, \(\beta_j\) is the fixed main effect of factor B at the \(j\)th level, and \((\alpha \beta)_{ij}\) is the interaction effect when factor A is at the \(i\)th level and factor B is at the \(j\)th level. For this model to be valid, it must have the following constraints: \[ \sum_{i=1}^a \alpha_i = 0, \ \ \ \ \sum_{j=1}^b \beta_j = 0, \] \[ \sum_{i=1}^a (\alpha \beta)_{ij} = 0 \ \ \ \text{and} \ \ \ \sum_{j=1}^b (\alpha \beta)_{ij} = 0 \] and it must meet the assumption that \(\varepsilon_{ijk}\) are i.i.d. (independently and identically distributed) as \(N(0,\sigma^2)\).

A Two-Way Anova model is balance if the number of observation by two categories are equal. The following table displays the number of observations by season and nationality.

##     
##      Fall Spring Summer Winter
##   CA  182    184    184    180
##   MX  182    184    184    180
##   US  182    184    184    180

Notice that these number are slightly different. This is because both Spring and Summer consist of two months with 31 days and one month with 30 days. The number of observations are smallest for Winter since it contains the month of February, which has the shortest number of days compared to all other months. Since the observations are large and do not differ much in size, we can say the a Two-Way ANOVA model applied to this data would be approximately balanced.

I believe that this model is appropriate for my task on studying the effects nationality and season have on the COVID death numbers since Two-Way ANOVA models give flexibility when the studying a quantitative variable using two categorical variables. Moreover, Two-Way ANOVA provides the ability to test whether main effects of each of the two categorical variables are present in the quantitative variable. Using a Two-Way ANOVA model for my question of interest, we will have the following representations:

  • \(Y_{ijk}\) is the cube-rooted number of deaths caused by COVID in the \(i\)th nation during the \(j\)th season.
  • \(\alpha_i\) is the main factor effect of nationality at the \(i\)th nation for \(i = 1,\ldots,a=3\) (three nations),
  • \(\beta_j\) is the main effect of seasonality at the \(j\)th season for \(j = 1, \ldots, b=4\) (four seasons),
  • \((\alpha \beta)_{ij}\) is the interaction effect when of the \(i\)th nation and \(j\)th season.

Model Fitting

Fitting a Two-Way ANOVA model using the cube-rooted number of COVID deaths, nationality and Season, we obtain the following results:

##                       Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)    
## Country_code           2  17768    8884 2480.97 <2e-16 ***
## Season                 3   1842     614  171.49 <2e-16 ***
## Country_code:Season    6   1157     193   53.86 <2e-16 ***
## Residuals           2178   7799       4                   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Note that the Country_code, Season, and the interaction between Country_Code and season have corresponding \(P\)-values less than \(2\times 10^{-16}\), which are very small \(P\)-values. This indicates that there is sufficient evidence to conclude that there are main effects from Nationality, main effects from Season, and interaction effects present in the cube-rooted number of deaths caused by COVID.

Model Diagnostics

I will now explore plots involving the residuals from the Two-Way ANOVA to see whether the model assumption that \(\varepsilon_{ijk}\) are i.i.d as \(N(0,\sigma^2)\).

Viewing the Residuals vs Fitted plot, one can see that variability among the residuals are not necessarily the same. Furthermore, the red-line in this plot deviates slightly from the dash-line. This indicates that the error terms do not necessarily have constance variance and mean 0. Looking at the Normal Q-Q plot, it appears that most of the points are on the gray dashed line. However, one can see that the points on the left deviate from the dashed-line. This indications that the distribution of the residuals is slightly left-skewed. The histogram of the residuals shows that the distribution of the residual is slight left-skewed and looks to be almost symmetric. Since the Two-Way ANOVA model that was fitted is approximately balanced, the results obtained from the model fitting are pretty robust against the normality assumption and unequal variance.

Since all bars shown in the plot stretch above the upper blue dashed-line, this suggests that the error terms are not necessarily dependent. One reason why this is the case in my situation is because the data Im working with are time observations, which are not randomized.

Discussion and Conclusion

Although it appears that model assumptions for the Two-Way ANOVA model that I fit werent necessarily, the results obtained from the fitting process are robust again most of these assumptions since the model is approximately balanced. Since the data im working with is time series data and observational data, thus making it difficult to correct for non-independence of the residuals. Although, the model give supporting evidence that season has effects in the number of COVID deaths per day, there maybe be other factors along with season that may cause the number of deaths to fluctuate. In the future, I would like to learn whether there are other variables play a role in these numbers. Indeed, each season of the year bring various challenges to these nations, such as cooler and warmer temperatures and flu season, that may potentially cause the COVID death numbers for these three nations to go up. # References

Kutner, M. H., Nachtsheim, C. J., Neter, J., & Li, W. (2005). Applied Linear Statistical Models / Michael H. Kutner et al.. McGraw-Hill Irwin.

Coronavirus Disease (COVID-19) Situation Reports. World Health Organization, World Health Organization, https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/situation-reports.

Appendix - R Code used

knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = TRUE)
library(lubridate)
library(gplots)
library(car)
library(MASS)
library(tidyverse)
covid <- read.csv("https://covid19.who.int/WHO-COVID-19-global-data.csv")
#Shortening data to US, CA, and MX
US <- which(covid$Country_code=="US")
CA <- which(covid$Country_code=="CA")
MX <- which(covid$Country_code=="MX")

covid_NA <- covid[c(US,CA,MX),]
#Creating Month and Year variables
covid_NA$Month <- month(covid_NA$Date_reported)
covid_NA$Year <- year(covid_NA$Date_reported)

Jan2020 <- which(covid_NA$Month==1 & covid_NA$Year==2020)
Feb2020 <- which(covid_NA$Month==2 & covid_NA$Year==2020)

covid_NA <- covid_NA[-c(Jan2020,Feb2020),]

#Creating Season variable 
covid_NA$Season <- c()
n_T <- nrow(covid_NA)

for (i in 1:n_T) {
  if (covid_NA$Month[i] == 1 | covid_NA$Month[i] == 2 | covid_NA$Month[i] == 12){
    covid_NA$Season[i] <- "Winter"
  }
  if (covid_NA$Month[i] == 3 | covid_NA$Month[i] == 4 | covid_NA$Month[i] == 5){
    covid_NA$Season[i] <- "Spring"
  }
  if (covid_NA$Month[i] == 6 | covid_NA$Month[i] == 7 | covid_NA$Month[i] == 8){
    covid_NA$Season[i] <- "Summer"
  }
  if (covid_NA$Month[i] == 9 | covid_NA$Month[i] == 10 | covid_NA$Month[i] == 11){
    covid_NA$Season[i] <- "Fall"
  }
}
covid_NA$Season <- as.factor(covid_NA$Season)
covid_NA$Country_code <- as.factor(covid_NA$Country_code)

covid_NA <- covid_NA[,-3]

# Removing all dates of March 2022 and beyond
March_2022 <- which(covid_NA$Month >= 3 & covid_NA$Year == 2022)
covid_NA <- covid_NA[-March_2022,]

rownames(covid_NA) <- 1:nrow(covid_NA)

#Creating Case Fatality Ratio Variable
covid_NA$New_CFR <- c()
for (i in 1:nrow(covid_NA)) {
  if(covid_NA$New_cases[i] == 0 ){
    covid_NA$New_CFR[i] = 0 
  }
  else{
    covid_NA$New_CFR[i] <- covid_NA$New_deaths[i]/covid_NA$New_cases[i]
  }
}
#View(covid_NA)
US_NA <- which(covid_NA$Country_code=="US")
CA_NA <- which(covid_NA$Country_code=="CA")
MX_NA <- which(covid_NA$Country_code=="MX")

t <- 1:length(covid_NA$New_deaths[US_NA])

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(t,covid_NA$New_deaths[US_NA],type='l', main="Number of Deaths due to 
     COVID-19", xlab="Time: March 1, 2020 - February 28, 2022", ylab="Number of Deaths")
lines(t,covid_NA$New_deaths[CA_NA],type='l',col=3)
lines(t,covid_NA$New_deaths[MX_NA],type='l',col=4)
legend("topleft", legend = c("US","CA","MX"), lty=c(1,1,1), col=c(1,3,4),
       cex=0.5)

plot(t,covid_NA$New_cases[US_NA],type='l', main="Number of Cases due to 
     COVID-19", xlab="Time: March 1, 2020 - February 28, 2022", ylab="Number of Deaths")
lines(t,covid_NA$New_cases[CA_NA],type='l',col=3)
lines(t,covid_NA$New_cases[MX_NA],type='l',col=4)
legend("topleft", legend = c("US","CA","MX"), lty=c(1,1,1), col=c(1,3,4),
       cex=0.5)
#par(mfrow=c(1,1))

plot(t,covid_NA$New_CFR[US_NA],type='l', main="Case Fatality Rate due to 
     COVID-19", xlab="Time: March 1, 2020 - February 28, 2022", ylab="Case
     Fatality Rate",ylim=c(0,.5))
lines(t,covid_NA$New_CFR[CA_NA],type='l',col=3)
lines(t,covid_NA$New_CFR[MX_NA],type='l',col=4)
legend("topright", legend = c("US","CA","MX"), lty=c(1,1,1), col=c(1,3,4),
       cex=0.5)
par(mfrow=c(1,1))
#aggregate(New_deaths~Country_code+Season,data=covid_NA,mean)
aggregate(list(Deaths=covid_NA$New_deaths,Cases=covid_NA$New_cases,
               CFR = covid_NA$New_CFR),
          by=list(Country=covid_NA$Country_code,Season=covid_NA$Season), mean)
covid_NA %>% 
  group_by(Country_code,Season) %>% 
  summarise(min = fivenum(New_deaths)[1],
            Q1 = fivenum(New_deaths)[2],
            median = fivenum(New_deaths)[3],
            Q3 = fivenum(New_deaths)[4],
            max = fivenum(New_deaths)[5])
covid_NA %>% 
  group_by(Country_code,Season) %>% 
  summarise(min = fivenum(New_cases)[1],
            Q1 = fivenum(New_cases)[2],
            median = fivenum(New_cases)[3],
            Q3 = fivenum(New_cases)[4],
            max = fivenum(New_cases)[5])
covid_NA %>% 
  group_by(Country_code,Season) %>% 
  summarise(min = round(fivenum(New_CFR)[1],4),
            Q1 = round(fivenum(New_CFR)[2],4),
            median = round(fivenum(New_CFR)[3],4),
            Q3 = round(fivenum(New_CFR)[4],4),
            max = round(fivenum(New_CFR)[5],4))
interaction.plot(covid_NA$Country_code,covid_NA$Season,covid_NA$New_deaths,
          xlab="Country", ylab="Average Number of Deaths by COVID",type="l", 
          lty=1, lwd=2, legend=T,col=c(2,3,4,5),trace.label="Season" )
table(covid_NA$Country_code,covid_NA$Season)
anova_model <- aov(I(New_deaths)^(1/3)~Country_code*Season,data=covid_NA)
summary(anova_model)
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(anova_model,which=c(1,2))
hist(anova_model$residuals,main="Histogram of Residuals",
     ylab="Residuals")
acf(anova_model$residuals,main="ACF plot of Residuals")
